}}'''Arthur "Art" Schultz''' (c. 1933) is an American [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrcc.org/news/view_article.asp?ID=668|title=More Line Up for Weller Vacancy|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2007-10-11|publisher=[[National Republican Congressional Committee]]}}</ref> He is the fifth-term [[mayor]] of {{city-state|Joliet|Illinois}}, which is the fourth largest municipality in the state,<ref name=AEotPfIPO1/> behind [[Chicago]], which is located {{convert|35|mi|km|1}} to the northeast,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/676.html|title=Joliet, IL|accessdate=2008-12-08|year=2005|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|author=Sterling, Robert E.}}</ref> [[Aurora, Illinois|Aurora]] and [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]].<ref name=AEotPfIPO1/>  He was last elected in April 2007.  Prior to his first election, he served in the [[United States Navy]] and in the Joliet Police Department.<ref name=MAS/>

His first attempt at public service was highly controversial because he finished as first runner-up in the Joliet [[City Council]] election of 1989.  When a sitting councilwoman passed away a few months after the election he was passed over several times for the nomination which customarily is given to the runner-up in the most recent election.<ref name=CEJD/>  He returned to elective politics to defeat the mayor who refused to nominate him in the subsequent election in 1991.<ref name=WCMC/>

In his time in office, the Joliet economy turned around from the economy of a stagnant prison town with declining population<ref name="cervin"/> to a fast growing entertainment and tourism economy.<ref name=Jotepttp/>  The city benefited from the [[casino]] industry which has provided unexpected revenue bounties.  Residential and commercial construction has blossomed and the community has seen racing tracks, a baseball stadium and several civic works develop as a result of the booming economy.<ref name=WslUig/>

==Personal==
He was born and raised in Joliet and attended [[parochial school]]s in the city.<ref name=MAS/>  He was an [[altar boy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF676686DD6AADE&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Return To A City of Friends - Joliet Throws Arms Around Weary But Elated Jenco|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1986-08-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Gibson, Ray and Rob Karwath}}</ref>  Schultz, like the two Joliet Mayors who preceded him, is a graduate of [[Joliet Catholic High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB427BF69B594FD&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Old Joliet Catholic High Is About To Be Born Again|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1996-08-09|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=O'Brien, Ken}}</ref> After high school, he served four years in the United States Navy during the [[Korean Conflict]].  He then worked for the Joliet Police Department for 29 years before being elected mayor in 1991.<ref name=MAS>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofjoliet.com/halloffame/politicians/artschultz.htm|title=Mayor Arthur Schultz|accessdate=2008-12-08|work=cityofjoliet.com}}</ref>

Schultz and his wife were married on November 6, 1954 at The Cathedral of St. Raymond.<ref name=KO3>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:JHNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1066C33F66A17D32&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Keepsakes Oct. 31, 04|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2004-10-31|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=The Herald News}}</ref> As of his fiftieth wedding anniversary in 2004, Schultz had five children and eight grandchildren.<ref name=MPRFTC/><ref name=MAS/>  His children are Debbie (married to Richard) Fonck, Nancy (Steve) Voots, Art (Nancy) Schultz, Dan (Sue) Schultz and Mike Schultz.<ref name=KO3/> On November 15, 2006, a [[grand jury]] in [[Will County, Illinois]] indicted his son, Arthur Schultz Jr., for official misconduct and tampering with public records, in a case involving fixing [[traffic ticket]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbs2chicago.com/local/joliet.arthur.schultz.2.333575.html|title=Arthur Schultz, Jr. One Of Two Charged Charged With Official Misconduct And Tampering With Public Records|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2006-11-16|publisher=CBS Broadcasting|work=cbs2chicago.com}}</ref> His daughter Nancy Schultz Voots, who celebrated her 25th anniversary a few months before her parent's 50th,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:JHNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=104423DAE76D386B&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Keepsakes July 18, 04|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2004-07-18|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=The Herald News}}</ref> is the Will County Clerk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.willclrk.com/home.htm|title=Office Of The Will County Clerk|accessdate=2008-12-12|publisher=Will County Clerk}}</ref>

On November 16, 1993 Schultz had a [[laryngectomy]] after having had [[vocal chord]] tumors removed the previous May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FFECF17848F9253&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Mayor Recuperating After Losing His Larynx To Cancer|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1993-11-11|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Elsner, David}}</ref>  Schultz lost his voice for a period before regaining it after several months of home recuperation with the aid of a voice [[prosthesis]] that was inserted into a neck valve.<ref name=MAS/><ref name=MPRFTC>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB42594A178F029&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Mayor Plans Return From Throat Cancer|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1994-02-01|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Shnay, Jeff}}</ref>

As of the July 1, 2007 [[United States Census Bureau]] population estimates, Joliet had a population of 144,316, which ranked it as the 162 largest incorporated municipality in the United States and the fourth largest in the state of Illinois.<ref name=AEotPfIPO1>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/tables/SUB-EST2007-01.xls|title=Annual Estimates of the Population for Incorporated Places Over 100,000, Ranked by July 1, 2007 Population: April 1, 2000 to July 1, 2007|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2008-07-10|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>

==Political career==
===Elections===
He ran for the election to the Joliet City Council during the Spring 1989 municipal elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF7E5AC0F0C116A&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=9 Seek 3 Seats On City Council|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1988-12-21|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  Schultz advanced from the February 28, 1989 [[primary election]] to the [[general election]] in what the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' described as a surprisingly strong showing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF78671EE8AEF8A&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=GOP Regulars Lose In Homer Township|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1989-03-01|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Merrifield, Bob}}</ref> but he finished fourth in the six-way April 4 general election race for three seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF7869ED2E7D7BB&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Will County - Municipal Election Results |accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1989-04-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  In August 1989, Joliet Councilwoman Margaret Short passed away with two years remaining in her term and Joliet Mayor Charles Connor had the responsibility of nominating a replacement for consideration by the remaining councilmen.  Instead of following the custom of nominating the first runner-up in the most recent council election (Schultz in this case), Connor nominated a political ally in September.  The council did not support the nomination and after some delay she withdrew her own name on September 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF78BBA7423BCE7&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet Mayor Stands By His Nominee|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1989-09-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Merrifield, Bob}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF78C7DB62A556F&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Mayor To Again Attempt To Fill Vacancy On Joliet City Council|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1989-09-21|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Merrifield, Bob}}</ref>  When Connor's second nomination was again not one of the runners-up, it was again defeated, which led to council legislation to strip him of his power to nominate councilmen.  On October 17, Connor became the first Joliet Mayor since the mid-1970s to refuse to sign legislation passed by the Joliet City Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF78DB439D9BA11&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet Mayor Rejects Law On Council Seat|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1989-10-18|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Slowik, Ted}}</ref> On November 21, there was unanimous agreement on a compromise candidate who was also not one of the runners-up.<ref name=CEJD>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF78F558C26F951&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Compromise Ends Joliet Deadlock|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1989-11-22|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Merrifield, Bob}}</ref>

At the time of the [[non-partisan]] February 26, 1991 Mayoral primary election, the ''Chicago Tribune'' described Joliet as suffering from stagnant economy and sagging population.  Between 1980 and 1990 the population had declined to 76,836 from 77,956, according to the [[United States Census Bureau]].<ref name="cervin"/>  Connor was challenged by three candidates, including Schultz.<ref name="cervin">{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FFEFEA591600BA8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet Incumbents Face Crowded Field|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1991-02-15|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Cervin, Jennifer}}</ref> Schultz narrowly won the primary election by a 2,709&ndash;2,545 (38%&ndash;36%) margin over Connor, but both candidates advanced to the April general election since they finished first and second in the primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB3733907770563&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Troiani gains Chicago Hts. mayoral runoff|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1991-02-27|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Franchine, Philip and Gary Wisby}}</ref> On April 2, Schultz won by a 6,081&ndash;5,534 margin.<ref name=WCMC>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FFF005685859A41&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Will County Municipal Contests|accessdate=2008-12-10|date=1991-04-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>

Schultz has been approved handily in his re-election bids.  In 1995, he earned 67 percent of the vote in the primary election and 68 percent in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB42695A0F5BD10&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Suburbs Sort Out the Also-Rans|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1995-03-01|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Caro, Mark and Jerry Shnay}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB426A792DA5850&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Will County Municipal Results|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1995-04-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  He was unopposed in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB42A4CB9B39EFC&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Will County Municipal Results|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1999-04-15|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> In 2003, he became the first four-term mayor for Joliet, which was incorporated in 1852, by taking 83% of the vote in a four-way contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FA45424046BBF60&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Will County Municipal Results|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2003-04-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F88FCDF1AE8417C&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet mayor to run for a 4th term|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2003-01-14|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=O'Brien, Ken}}</ref>  In 2007, he earned 73% of the vote in a three-way contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11E915E1A9645810&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Mayoral Races|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2007-04-18|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>

===Service===
In June 1989, with the blessing of Will County officials,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF786DCE724C1EB&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=River Gambling Gets Cautious OK|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1989-05-28|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Pearson, Rick and A. Dahleen Glanton}}</ref> the [[Illinois Senate]] approved [[riverboat gambling]] by passing two bills that permit gambling along the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]], [[Illinois River|Illinois]] and [[Des Plaines River]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF786E2C36A1367&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Let 'Em Roll On The Mississippi|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1989-06-02|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref>  Both houses of the [[Illinois General Assembly]] agreed on riverboat gambling in January of 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF827382A73F947&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Riverboat Gambling Squeaks In - Tax Relief Fizzles; Floating-Casino Bill Goes To Governor|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1990-01-12|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Egler, Daniel and Rick Pearson}}</ref> but gambling did not commence in Joliet until June 17, 1992.<ref name=BotrJIltmtEcg>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:KCSB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EAF3ED7B036F568&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Bounty on the riverbank Joliet , Ill., loves the money that Empress casino generates|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1993-01-31|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|author=Fitzpatrick, James C.}}</ref>  However, by January 1993, gambling in Joliet was so successful that Schultz described Joliet as "the riverboat-gambling capital of the world".<ref name=BotrJIltmtEcg/>  In October 1993, Schultz noted that crime in the city declined with the advent of gambling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:KCSB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EAF401FE87250CC&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Star's editorial position on gambling is piety minus the facts|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1994-02-07|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|author=Rimbo, Bruce}}</ref>  The first few years of gambling were so successful that by 1995, before [[Indiana]] approved gambling, Joliet expected to be debt free in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:RTDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB4F9C909C42FA6&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Greening Of Joliet Shows What Casino Cash Can Do|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1995-01-10|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|author=Smith, Randolph P.}}</ref>  Schultz described the surprisingly sizable gambiling industry revenues as "[[manna]] from Heaven" and encouraged other cities to try legalized gambling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:PHIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB32CFE40F343E1&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Rendell Renews Effort To Get Riverboat Gambling Here< He's Moving and Shaking To Get A Statewide Referendum.< If It Fails, Time For Plan B. Then Plan C.|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1996-03-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|author=Nicholas, Peter}}</ref>

Between 1993 and 1997 Schultz only received a total of [[US$]]1,500 in gambling-related political contributions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:SLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB05026DE9B7C20&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Boat Gives Bush Big Donations, But He Denies Conflict|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1997-02-02|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|author=McDermott, Kevin}}</ref>  During the 1990s, Joliet was one of the fastest growing cities in the state, and in 2000 its residential and commercial construction were at record-setting levels, according to Schultz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:OMIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FDA23FFCE96F767&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Bays: Casino answer to job goals Hotel owner says he could bring in thousands of high-paying jobs|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2001-07-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Owensboro Messenger-Inquirer]]|author=Lawrence,  Keith}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://illinoisgis.ito.state.il.us/census2000/dplace_census.asp?theSelCnty=001|title=Illinois Census 2000|accessdate=2008-12-08|publisher=www.illinois.gov}}</ref>  Schultz also credits gambling revenues with having enabled the city to halt tax increases for a decade and to build a new police station and three new firehouses.<ref name=WslUig>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:MBRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FC4A7D4AC29A66B&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Western suburbs lead U.S. in growth|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2003-07-10|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Mobile Register]]|author=Armas, Genaro C.}}</ref>  Despite the success and growth Joliet has seen there have been disappointments such as the fact that Harrah's Joliet Casino did not build its hotel nearly as quickly as Schultz would have liked.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:GPTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10848FD71535D552&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Harrah's Acquires Showboat|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1998-06-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Post-Tribune]]|author=Rhye, Shirley M.}}</ref>

In 1999, the Joliet City Council approved the construction of the [[Chicagoland Speedway]] on {{convert|930|acre|km2|2}} of land next to the [[Route 66 Raceway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DTHB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EAE4D5CE3A671A2&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet Council Annexes Land For Auto Racetrack|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=1999-01-21|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Telegraph Herald]]}}</ref>  Between 2000 and 2002 Joliet was the tenth fastest growing city in the United States.<ref name=WslUig/> Under Schultz, the city ended nearly 150 years as a prison town with the closure of the [[Joliet Correctional Center]] and focussed its economy on entertainment and tourism.<ref name=Jotepttp>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1137C06CB1E02488&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet out to escape past ties to prison - City says its image is no longer behind bars |accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2006-08-13|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Dardick, Hal}}</ref>

[[Silver Cross Field]], which was built in 2002 to host the [[Joliet Jackhammers]] of the [[Northern League (baseball)|Northern League]] is located at 1 Mayor Art Schultz Dr.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jackhammerbaseball.com/contact/contactinfo/|title=The Official Web Site of the Joliet Jackhammers|accessdate=2008-12-07|publisher=Joliet Jackhammers}}</ref>

Joliet's growth is partly due to a series of successful but contentious annexations that occurred under Schultz.  In the early 1990s the city annexed {{convert|55|acre|km2}} for the construction of the Empress Riverboat Casino complex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FFEE366B4E27C32&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=The Riverboat Gamble - Some Towns Win, Others End Up Short|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1992-08-17|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Morris, Steven}}</ref>  In 1999, the city annexed {{convert|923|acre|km2}} for the construction of the Chicagoland Speedway, which when combined with the Route 66 Raceway made Joliet the only racing facility host in the United States capable of hosting races from each major category in professional [[auto racing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:SJRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB149BDABCE0428&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet may Combine NHRA, NASCAR Events|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1999-01-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The State Journal-Register]]|author=Okon, Bob}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB42A1F17D0588F&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet Annexes Racetrack Site - Speedway To Attract Jobs, Tax Revenue|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1999-01-20|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Ziemba, Stanley}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB42A18C0637CFE&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet Now In Running For Auto Racetrack - Public Hearing Jan. 19 On 75,000-Seat Proposal|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=1999-01-07|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Ziemba, Stanley}}</ref>  In 2001, the city acquired 12 parcels totaling {{convert|8|acre|m2}} through expedited [[condemnation]]s to build Silver Cross Field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0ECF19925C73EC53&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet Putting Ballpark Plan On A Faster Track - City OKs Quick-Take Condemnations For A Downtown Stadium|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2001-01-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=O'Brien, Ken}}</ref>  In 2005, the city annexed {{convert|988|acre|km2}} to provide a growth corridor for commercial and residential growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1080827E500DEA7C&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Joliet adds 988 acres for growth - Land near I-80 annexed, slated for residential and commercial use|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2005-02-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=O'Brien, Ken}}</ref>  By 2007, the recent history of prosperous growth and prospects of continued future growth necessitated that Joliet agree on borders with one neighboring municipality and that it consider future borders with others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:JHNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11C66D177B627FD8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Creeping Through Kendall, The City Has A Future Limit Joliet Sets Boundary With -Oswego|accessdate=2008-12-12|date=2007-10-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=The Herald News|author=Okon, Bob}}</ref>

